Github Copilot License Request and Setup Guide
A.	Github Copilot License:

1.	Go to https://wiprocio.service-now.com/sp and search for “Github Copilot” on the search bar of the landing page as below. In the drop down select the option “Service Request for GitHub Copilot Standalone License (WC4C)

 

2.	In the subsequent requisition form, enter the details and submit the request. 
3.	Once the request is processed, you would receive a confirmation of license allotment usually within 24 hours.
4.	Meanwhile, you should have also received a mail from “Github” email ID confirming your license and the mail would contain the user-id   that you need to use to sign-in when you add the “Github Copilot Chat” extension on your VS Code IDE.

B.	VS Code (Visual Studio Code) IDE Installation
a.	We will be using VS Code IDE during this training. 
b.	In case you do not have the VS Code IDE on your machine, raise a requisition for the same https://wiprocio.service-now.com/sp  -> "other portals" tab -> catalog -> left panel in the "Explore Catalog" section choose "software request" and expand it to see -> Open Source -> search for “"Visual Studio code" software (preferably version 1.92 or above)  (This will be an Integrated Development Environment (IDE) and fill in the details (for the option - 'purpose of usage' you can choose "Evaluation or Training".

C.	Install the “GitHub Copilot Chat” extensions on VS Code IDE
a.	Install the “GitHub Copilot Chat” extensions on VS Code IDE
b.	In earlier versions, installing the “Github Copilot” extension also was needed, but now, this is deprecated.
 
c.	Once the extension is successfully added, in the left bottom accounts icon, you can sign-in to your account using the user-id that you had received earlier from a Github mail. 

 

d.	Since the user-id is enabled with SSO (Single Sign-On), a password entry is not needed.
e.	Once the sign-in is successful, you should be able to now start using the Github Copilot and its features in your IDE


Step1: Install dependencies
Add the MCP SDK and zod dependency (needs Node 18+)
 (Zod is a TypeScript-first schema validation library that provides a simple and powerful way to define, validate, and transform data structures. Zod is widely used in various applications, including API validation, form validation, and runtime type checking)
npm install @modelcontextprotocol/sdk
npm install zod

Step2: Create MCP server 
create a new server entry file in the project root with this content: (bank-server.js)
// Import required dependencies from the Model Context Protocol SDK
const { McpServer } = require("@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/mcp.js");
const { StdioServerTransport } = require("@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js");
const { z } = require("zod");

// Sample bank accounts data with id, customer name, and account balance
const accounts = [
    { id: 1, name: "Alice", balance: 5000.0 },      // Alice's account with $5000
    { id: 2, name: "Bob", balance: 3200.5 },        // Bob's account with $3200.50
    { id: 3, name: "Charlie", balance: 150.75 }     // Charlie's account with $150.75
];

// Initialize the MCP server with name and version
const server = new McpServer({
  name: "bank-demo-server",
  version: "1.0.0"
});

// Tool 1: List all customer accounts
server.registerTool(
  "list_accounts",
  {
    description: "Return all customer accounts",
    inputSchema: {} // No input parameters required
  },
  async () => {
    // Return all accounts in both text and structured formats
    return {
      content: [
        {
          type: "text",
          text: JSON.stringify(accounts, null, 2)
        }
      ],
      structuredContent: {
        accounts
      }
    };
  }
);

// Tool 2: Get a specific account by its numeric ID
server.registerTool(
  "get_account_by_id",
  {
    description: "Get a customer account by numeric id",
    inputSchema: {
      // Define input parameter: id must be a positive integer
      id: z.number().int().positive().describe("Customer account id")
    }
  },
  async ({ id }) => {
    // Search for account with matching ID
    const account = accounts.find((item) => item.id === id);

    // Return error if account not found
    if (!account) {
      return {
        content: [
          {
            type: "text",
            text: `No account found for id ${id}`
          }
        ],
        isError: true
      };
    }

    // Return the found account
    return {
      content: [
        {
          type: "text",
          text: JSON.stringify(account, null, 2)
        }
      ],
      structuredContent: {
        account
      }
    };
  }
);

// Tool 3: Find accounts with balance below a threshold
server.registerTool(
  "find_accounts_below_balance",
  {
    description: "Find accounts with balance less than or equal to a maximum amount",
    inputSchema: {
      // Define input parameter: maximum balance threshold (non-negative)
      maxBalance: z.number().nonnegative().describe("Maximum balance")
    }
  },
  async ({ maxBalance }) => {
    // Filter accounts matching the balance criteria
    const matches = accounts.filter((item) => item.balance <= maxBalance);

    // Return matching accounts with count
    return {
      content: [
        {
          type: "text",
          text: JSON.stringify(matches, null, 2)
        }
      ],
      structuredContent: {
        matches,
        count: matches.length
      }
    };
  }
);

// Main function to start the server
async function main() {
  // Create stdio transport for server communication
  const transport = new StdioServerTransport();
  // Connect server to transport
  await server.connect(transport);
  console.error("bank-demo-server is running over stdio");
}

// Execute main function and handle any errors
main().catch((error) => {
  console.error("Server error:", error);
  process.exit(1);
});

