  }
}

Step 4: Register the Server in VS Code
Invoke the Command Palette (ctrl+shift+p) and then type or select: MCP: Open workspace Folder Configuration
This opens the workspace MCP config file. Put below into it: (this is preferred on Windows) (Current project folder -> .vscode/mcp.json)
{
  "servers": {
    "bank-demo": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["bank-server.js"]
    }
  }
}
Explanation: A stdio MCP server is a locally launched process that speaks the MCP protocol through standard input/output pipes rather than over a web endpoint.

Alternatively if using the npm script:
{
  "servers": {
    "bank-demo": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "npm",
      "args": ["run", "mcp:bank"]
    }
  }
}
Step 5: Start and Trust the Server. After saving the MCP configuration:
a.	VS Code should detect the new server
b.	You will be asked whether to trust it
c.	Accept the trust prompt
d.	Using command palette -> Run -> MCP: List Servers if needed and start it manually.
e.	Open Chat and use Configure Tools to verify the server tools are enabled

If server fails to start, use: command palette-> 

MCP: List Servers

Then choose:

Show Output

That log is the fastest way to diagnose MCP startup issues

Step 6: Use it in Chat
Once the server is running, you can ask copilot things like

•	Use the bank-demo MCP tools to list all customer accounts.

•	Use the get_account_by_id tool for id 2 and summarize the result.

•	Which customer has the lowest balance? Use the MCP tools.

•	Find all accounts with balance below 1000.

(For a training session, be explicit with the tool usage in the prompt. That’s makes the demo more reliable than waiting for the model to decide on its own)

Good Demo Flow:

A simple training sequence:
a.	List all accounts using the MCP tool
b.	Get account id 1
c.	Find accounts below 1000
d.	Who has the smallest balance
e.	Summarize the dataset as a banker would

That shows:
a.	Tool discovery
b.	Tool invocation
c.	Parameter passing
d.	Model reasoning on top of tool output
